# generally via image_slack_nonneg (on-edge image point in every half-plane) +
# hp_slack affine-in-x, no cross-monotonicity.  The geometric keystone behind the
# convex residuals; exterior-even is a theorem given the straddling edges
# (exterior_slice_contra).  Validated on the diamond.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/ConvexSlice.v
# HexagonOffringSeam: the convex HEXAGON as the FIFTH total off-ring JCT family
# and the FIRST convex polygon with more than four edges (n = 6).  Presents
# hexagon_ring by its six edge inward half-planes (hexagon_edge_hps); interior-
# odd via RUNG 4 (hexagon_interior_chain_hit) + bimonotone_split_parity;
# exterior-even via a six-edge per-band case analysis using the ray guards.
# hexagon_parity_seam_offring : forall p, parity_characterises_interior_cont_offring
# p hexagon_ring.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/HexagonOffringSeam.v
# ConvexExteriorEven: the GENERAL exterior-even, factoring the parity bridge out
# of every family.  Isolates the geometric heart as the named predicate
# convex_exterior_balanced (exterior point's ray crosses the two chains
# both-or-neither); convex_exterior_even_of_balanced turns it into ~point_in_ring
# for any bimonotone_split ring, and convex_offring_seam_of_balanced composes it
# into a general convex off-ring seam.  Validated on diamond + hexagon.  The
# genuinely-hard discharge of the predicate for arbitrary convex rings (the
# convex slice fact) stays the named residual.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/ConvexExteriorEven.v
# ConvexJCT: the convex Jordan characterization, GEOMETRIC form -- ray-parity
# point_in_ring agrees with the convex field conv_min for a y-unimodal convex
# ring, by composing interior-odd (interior_hits_one_chain_of_edge_hps) with
# exterior-even (convex_exterior_balanced_of_unimodal) through
# bimonotone_split_parity.  No open residual; validated on diamond + hexagon.
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/ConvexJCT.v
# H1 PROPER, part 1: the transport engine + the reduction of the "trapped"
# half to one analytic kernel.  Parity decidability (edge_crosses_ray_dec,
# ray_parity_dec/_excl, point_in_ring_dec); invariant_transport_along_path
# (a decidable locally-stable predicate is constant along a path -- pure
# completeness-of-R, the decidability replaces hidden classical choice);
# invariant_traps / odd_parity_trapped_of_invariant (ANY ring: an odd-parity
# point agreeing with a decidable, complement-locally-constant, far-false
# invariant is in a bounded component).  The remaining kernel is constructing
# that invariant for a general simple ring (the HALF-OPEN parity -- the
# strict parity is NOT locally constant: a far-west point's count jumps at a
# pass-through-vertex height).  Non-vacuity: the rectangle instantiates the
# reduction via the box-field sign (rect_trapped_via_invariant).
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTParityTransport.v
# H1 PROPER, part 2: the HALF-OPEN ray parity (edge counts when vy <= h < wy)
# -- the locally-constant invariant the transport engine was built for.
# Decidability + exclusivity; guard agreement with the strict parity under
# ray_avoids_vertices alone (the conventions differ only at bottom-endpoint
# heights, where the crossing IS the vertex); far-field evenness in all FOUR
# directions -- right/up/down by no-crossing, WEST by the cyclic walk
# argument (far west, an edge crosses iff its endpoints' below-flags differ;
# around a CLOSED walk the flag returns home, so flips are even -- the place
# closedness genuinely enters).  Capstone odd_parity_trapped_of_ho_kernel:
# the trapped half of H1 for ANY closed ring now follows from the single
# named kernel ho_parity_locally_constant (local constancy along complement
# paths -- the y-monotone vertex-pairing content).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTHalfOpenParity.v
# H1 PROPER, part 3: GENERIC-HEIGHT local constancy of the half-open parity,
# Qed -- and the kernel shrinks to vertex-level points.  At a complement
# point off all vertex heights, every per-edge crossing condition is a
# conjunction of STRICT affine signs (the ray atom PA/PD is nonzero because
# zero-in-band puts the point ON the edge); affine_sign_stable gives explicit
# balls, ho_parity_ball Rmin's them over the edge list, path continuity
# lifts to the parameter (path_coord_close).  ho_kernel_of_level_stable:
# the full kernel ho_parity_locally_constant follows from ho_level_stable
# (constancy at VERTEX-LEVEL complement points only -- the pure vertex-
# pairing content).  Capstone odd_parity_trapped_of_level_stable: H1's
# trapped half now needs ONLY ho_level_stable.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTGenericStability.v
# H1 PROPER, part 4: UPPER half-ball constancy of the half-open parity at
# EVERY complement point, Qed (the bottom-inclusive band makes parity equal
# its limit from above: per edge only four upper-regimes -- dead-above,
# unreached, live-ascending-with-bottom, live-descending-with-bottom; the
# live ray atoms PA/PD are nonzero with the t=0 witness allowed, so no
# genericity and no pairing).  ho_upper_stable; the kernel shrinks to
# ho_level_jump (parity just BELOW a vertex level equals parity AT it --
# the east level-vertices' band-handover count, isolated on one side of one
# line); ho_level_stable_of_jump; capstone odd_parity_trapped_of_level_jump:
# H1's trapped half from the single downward-jump statement.
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTLevelJump.v
# H1 PROPER, part 5: THE TRAPPED HALF OF THE POLYGONAL JCT, Qed and
# UNCONDITIONAL.  The east-level flag F(v) := (py v = level /\ px q < px v)
# satisfies, per edge, (cross-below <-> cross-at) <-> (F fst <-> F snd) --
# nine cases, with horizontal level edges having both endpoints on one side
# of a complement point -- so the downward jump telescopes around the closed
# walk (ho_jump_walk / ho_jump_closed) exactly like the far-west lemma.
# ho_level_jump_holds proves the part-4 kernel; odd_parity_trapped: a
# ray-guarded odd-parity point is in a bounded complement component of ANY
# closed ring (ring_simple NOT needed).  The load-bearing half of H1.
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTTrappedHalf.v
# H1 PROPER, assembly: the kernel chain named (ho_parity_locally_constant_
# holds for every closed ring); the seam's hard direction unconditional
# (point_in_ring_imp_geometric_cont: odd guarded off-ring points of any
# closed ring are geometric-interior); the ESCAPE residual isolated
# (even_parity_escapes -- the only place simplicity is needed: doubly-wound
# rings have even trapped points); parity_seam_offring_of_escape /
# point_in_ring_correct_of_escape derive the FULL corrected seam from it
# (the parity side decided by point_in_ring_dec, no classical step).
# Sanity: the rectangle discharges the residual at a concrete point.
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTSeamAssembly.v
# H1 PROPER, part 6: the escape half decomposed.  ho_count (decidable
# nat-valued crossing count) + parity bridge; BASE CASE Qed
# (escape_east_of_zero_count: zero crossings + the ray guard make the open
# eastward ray literally skeleton-free -- strict straddles east would be
# counted, vertices/horizontal level edges east are banished by the guard
# -- so the straight ray escapes); STRONG INDUCTION Qed (escape_of_descent,
# riding in_bounded_component_cont_invariant).  THE FINAL RESIDUAL:
# escape_descent -- one detour, one fewer crossing; simplicity lives here
# and only here.  parity_seam_offring_of_descent: the FULL corrected H1
# seam from the descent step alone.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTEscapeDescent.v
# H1 PROPER, part 7: THE SEPARATION CLAUSE OF THE JCT, unconditional --
# parity_constant_on_components (guarded endpoints of a complement path have
# equal strict parity: transport + half-open kernel + guard agreement) and
# odd_even_separated (inside and outside never meet through the complement
# of ANY closed ring; no simplicity).  This is the separation clause PR #82
# added to the JCT_two_components_cont hypothesis, now a THEOREM.  Plus the
# escape residual discharged on every total family (rect/gtri/rtri
# even_parity_escapes, each by the family field trichotomy).
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTSeparation.v
# H_bridge geometric route (Rung 3b-iv), Phase B brick: discrete parity
# transport across a ring-clear straight segment, reduced to
# parity_constant_on_components.  Reusable primitive for the bridge's
# crossing-number argument.
theories/SegmentParityTransport.v
# H_bridge geometric route (Rung 3b-iv), Phase B step 3a: single-edge parity
# flip -- agreeing off one edge and straddling it gives opposite point-in-ring
# parity (the combinatorial core of the "opposite parity across edge d" step).
theories/EdgeCrossParity.v
# H_bridge Euler route (Rung 3b-iv), Phase C-1: cycle/orbit counting for a
# finite injective self-map -- same-orbit equivalence + decidability +
# cycle_count. Combinatorial substrate for the face-count (Euler) accounting.
theories/PermCycleCount.v
# H_bridge Euler route (Rung 3b-xvii, stage 1 of the cycle-count splice): the
# generic orbit-transversal substrate (orbit_reps_indep/_NoDup, orbit_rep_in,
# orbit_reps_length_mono) for counting same_orbit classes.  No Admitteds.
theories/PermCycleSplice.v
# H_bridge Euler route (Rung 3b-iv), Phase C NL-1: E_minus arrangement
# scaffolding -- removing an edge only removes darts (incl), fan_ok is
# downward-closed, so arrangement_ok survives edge removal; plus the exact
# dart-removal membership characterisation when the opposite orientation is
# absent (the bridge setting ~ In (twin e) E).
theories/ArrangementEMinus.v
# H_bridge Euler route (Rung 3b-xv): the pointwise SURGERY description of fstep
# under edge deletion (fstep_E_minus_splice) -- composes fstep_E_minus_eq_away +
# next_remove.  The input to the num_faces cycle-count splice.  No Admitteds.
theories/FaceStepRemove.v
# H_bridge Euler route (Rung 3b-vi): num_faces -- the number of fstep-orbits
# (faces) of darts_of E, via cycle_count; well-defined and positive for any
# nonempty general-position arrangement. (num_components lands in ReachableDec.)
theories/MapCounts.v
# H_bridge Euler route (Rung 3b, stage 5): instantiate the generic cycle-count
# splice (PermCycleSplice.cycle_count_surgery) at the face permutation --
# num_faces_E_minus_splice: deleting a same-face edge raises num_faces by one.
theories/NumFacesSplice.v
# H_bridge Euler route (Rung 3b-viii): num_vertices / num_edges + the Euler
# identity V+F=E+2*C as a NAMED HYPOTHESIS (not an axiom), plus the edge-count
# deletion instance num_edges_E_minus.  No Admitteds.
theories/EulerArrangement.v
# H_bridge Euler route (Rung 3b-xi/-xii/-xvi): WIRING -- euler_component_increase
# (Euler V-E+F=2C + same-face FACE SPLIT => C'=C+1) + reachable_E_minus_of_bypass
# assemble into H_bridge_core_conclusion_from_euler.  No Admitteds.
theories/EulerBridge.v
# Vertex invariance under single-edge deletion (face_twin_free closure rung 1 /
# H7): num_vertices (E_minus E e) = num_vertices E from no_spurs (min-degree-2).
# Discharges the carried vertex-count hypothesis of the Euler bridge.  No Admitteds.
theories/VertexDegree.v
# Non-vacuity witnesses for the carried planar-Euler premise euler_characteristic
# (single edge; two disjoint edges, validating the 2*C coefficient).  No Admitteds.
theories/EulerWitness.v
# H_bridge Euler route (Rung 3b, stage 6): discharge the named bridge premise
# EdgeFaceBridge.H_bridge_premise from the planar Euler identity (via
# H_bridge_core_conclusion_from_euler + num_faces_E_minus_splice).  No Admitteds.
theories/HBridgeEuler.v
# H_bridge Euler route (Rung 3b-vii, PR #194): generic decidable-relation class
# counter (count_classes) -- order-independent counting core.
theories/ClassCount.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 1 (docs/jct-escape-descent-plan.md): the east
# approach.  cross_x (crossing abscissa; guard makes every half-open
# crossing a STRICT straddle, so it is the edge's unique height point,
# strictly east); min_cross_x (the first wall: existence, achievement,
# lower bound); east_segment_free (the run-up [px p, X1) is skeleton-free);
# east_approach (every run-up point is complement-connected, off-ring,
# guarded, with the SAME ho_count); crossings_distinct -- the first genuine
# use of ring_simple in the H1 campaign: distinct crossing edges cross at
# distinct abscissae (a shared point is interior to both strict straddles,
# hence a proper intersection).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTEastApproach.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 2: the corridor toolkit.  The carrier line edge_x_at
# is AFFINE in height, so the corridor (edge_x_at y - delta, y) is itself a
# STRAIGHT segment (corridor_connected via straight_path_continuous), and
# every clearance is an affine endpoint evaluation: corridor_avoid_carrier
# (any positive offset), _west (endpoints west by more than delta), _east,
# _below/_above (outside the height window) -- explicit margins, no
# compactness, no square roots.  level_gap/guard_of_fresh_level: an explicit
# vertex-level-free parking height above any y0 gives the ray guard for
# free.  Worked instance: a corridor inside the unit square with every
# clearance discharged by the helpers.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTCorridor.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 3: the walk kit.  The MIXED clearance via the
# three-point affine law (s1-s0)*F s = (s1-s)*F s0 + (s-s0)*F s1 (a ring
# fact): an edge whose window-overlap parameters are clipped into [s0,s1]
# and whose clearance F beats delta at both clip points clears the whole
# overlap (corridor_avoid_clipped_west/_east); clip_params_asc/_desc compute
# the clip points by affine inversion (Rmax/Rmin clamps).  Jog connectors
# horizontal_connected / vertical_connected glue consecutive corridor
# pieces along skeleton-free axis segments.  Generic geometry complete;
# rung 4 = per-polygon touch-freedom (ring_simple), corner sectors, and the
# bounded boundary recursion.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTWalkKit.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 4: the assembled WALK STEP.  The crossing abscissa IS
# the carrier line's abscissa at p's height (cross_x_is_edge_x_at), so the
# east run-up endpoint and the corridor top coincide
# (corridor_top_is_wall_point); crossing edges are non-horizontal under the
# guard (crossing_edge_nonhorizontal); exists_parked_height parks the lower
# end in a vertex-level-free gap (free ray guard).  walk_step: east run-up +
# wall corridor glued by connectivity transitivity, conditional only on the
# corridor clearances; walk_step_guarded delivers a connected, off-ring,
# guarded destination.  Rung 5 = clearances from ring_simple touch-freedom,
# corner choice, recursion.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTWalkStep.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 4b-1: the TAUT bridge.  ring_taut (edges meet only at
# shared endpoints; the pointwise-equal-edges escape hatch absorbs the
# undecidable carrier case semantically); ring_taut_implies_simple (taut
# strengthens the corpus predicate, which deliberately admits T-touches);
# taut_no_line_touch (inside a span-interior window the carrier's LINE and
# SEGMENT coincide, so any edge meeting the line there IS the carrier
# pointwise -- the sign-orienting consumer for every clearance);
# affine_root (constructive IVT for affine functions, explicit -B/A root
# with sign-split bound proofs); clip_ordered_asc/_desc (clip points
# ordered, in [0,1], heights inside the window).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTTautClearance.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 4b-2: THE WALL THEOREM (wall_corridor_clear).  For a
# taut ring and a wall edge spanning a span-interior window, the corridor at
# offset delta is skeleton-free for ALL delta in (0, delta0) -- the uniform
# delta0 the walk step (rung 4) consumes.  touch_clearance: any touch
# witness forces edge = carrier pointwise via taut_no_line_touch, so
# corridor_avoid_carrier clears it -- the unifying trick absorbing every
# zero/sign-change branch.  per_edge_clear: the case tree (ascending /
# horizontal / descending obstacle x below / above / west / east / touch),
# clipped clearances G0/G1 at the window clip points, sign-change roots via
# affine_root; every clearance is an affine endpoint evaluation (no
# compactness, no square roots).  clear_fold: generic Rmin fold over the
# edge list.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTWallClear.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 4b-3: THE CORNER SECTOR (corner_sector_guarded).  The
# wall theorem clears corridors only span-interior; to descend past the wall
# edge's bottom vertex v the walk drops VERTICALLY just west of v, from
# py v + eps to py v - eps, with eps shrunk after delta (edges incident to v
# stay within slope*eps of v, short of the delta/2 offset).  Tautness enters
# once more: an edge through v has v as a shared endpoint
# (taut_vertex_endpoint), so obstacles split into edges AT v (slope bound)
# and edges MISSING v (explicit positive margins at v's level, level_gap
# style); two-stage Rmin fold corner_fold gives uniform delta0 then
# eps0(delta).  Honest residual hypothesis: no horizontal edge extends WEST
# from v (it would block every drop; deferred to the rung-5 recursion).
# Also: corridor_offset_jog (corridors of two offsets connect at a shared
# height) and depth_gap (parking BELOW a level with a free ray guard).
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTCornerSector.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5a: the CORNER-ABUTTING WALL CLEARANCE
# (wall_corridor_clear_corner), dissolving the quantifier deadlock between
# the wall theorem (window before delta) and the corner drop (eps after
# delta).  Under corner_opens_east -- every edge incident at the wall's
# bottom vertex v reaching weakly above v's level stays weakly EAST of the
# wall's carrier -- the corridor is free on ALL of (py v, yhi] with ONE
# uniform delta0: incident edges clear at any offset
# (corridor_avoid_east_weak), descending incidents sit below the open
# window, and non-incident edges NEVER touch the carrier on [py v, yhi]
# (touch at the corner level = touch at v itself -> taut_vertex_endpoint;
# touch above = span-interior -> taut_no_line_touch -> pointwise-equal ->
# incident; both contradictions), so the rung 4b-2 clip tree runs with
# eps-free margins.  This hypothesis is exactly where INSIDE walkers stick
# (the wedge companion ascends west), as odd_parity_trapped demands.
# corner_passage composes ride + drop: corridor at yhi to an off-ring,
# guarded point strictly below the corner level.  Subsumes 4b-3's
# horizontal residual (opens_east_horizontal).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTCornerClear.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5b: THE MIRROR KIT.  The boundary-hugging walk needs
# corridor moves in all four orientations (west/east of a wall, under
# bottoms / over tops); instead of hand-writing three mirrored kits, this
# transports the complement geometry through the coordinate reflections
# xmir (east<->west) and ymir (over<->under): ring_edges/ring_image/
# ring_complement/ring_taut/ring_closed/connected_in_complement_cont
# (continuity_opp) / in_bounded_component_cont (norm reflection-invariant),
# each both ways via involutions.  The horizontal ray makes ymir EXACT for
# the crossing data: guard, edge_crosses_ray_ho, ho_count, parity all
# transport (under the guard every half-open crossing is a strict straddle,
# and strictness is y-symmetric).  xmir reverses the ray, so it carries
# freedom/connectivity only (east-side corridors = west corridors of the
# mirror); counts are recomputed at endpoints.  Every west/under theorem of
# rungs 2-5a now applies verbatim to the mirrored rings and pulls back
# along connected_xmir_rev / connected_ymir_rev.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTMirrorKit.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-1: THE TOP PASSAGE and the TERMINAL COUNT.  First
# consumer of the mirror kit: corner_passage pulled back through the y-flip
# gives corner_passage_top -- from the wall's west corridor at any
# span-interior height, over the wall's TOP vertex, to an off-ring,
# ray-guarded point strictly ABOVE the top level: the move that backs the
# walk out of a sealed wedge.  Mirrored hypothesis corner_opens_east_top in
# original coordinates (incident edges reaching weakly BELOW u stay weakly
# east of the carrier); the guard pulls back exactly (rung 5b's y-flip
# exactness).  edge_x_at_ymir/_xmir relate the carrier across the flips.
# Terminal payoff: xsup (east-most vertex abscissa, explicit Rmax fold);
# at or east of it no edge crosses the ray (crossing abscissa is a convex
# combination of endpoint abscissae), so ho_count_zero_east: count ZERO --
# what escape_east_of_zero_count consumes.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTTopPassage.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-2: THE FOUR-ORIENTATION PASSAGE KIT.  The corner
# moves in all four orientations, with uniform interfaces.  The x-flip
# reverses the eastward ray and cannot transport the ray guard -- but the
# passage destinations are parked at LEVEL-FRESH heights (depth_gap), and a
# level-fresh point is guarded in every direction (ray_guard_of_fresh).
# corner_passage_fresh re-assembles rung 5a's composition with the parking
# margin folded into eps0 explicitly, exposing freshness; the mirrors then
# give corner_passage_top_fresh (west/over, ymir), corner_passage_east
# (east/under, xmir; condition corner_opens_west) and
# corner_passage_east_top (east/over, xmir o ymir; corner_opens_west_top).
# Each: one complement path from the side-corridor at any span-interior
# height, around the corner, to an off-ring point strictly past the corner
# level, plus level freshness of the destination height.  Three-axiom.
# No Admitted.
theories/JCTPassageKit.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-3: THE UNDER-TIP CROSSING.  At a LOCAL-MINIMUM
# corner (every incident edge reaches weakly upward) the horizontal band
# just below v is skeleton-free across the whole corner
# [px v - 2*delta, px v + 2*delta]: the side-switch move connecting the
# west-side passage destinations to the east-side corridors (y-flip: over
# a local-maximum tip).  Incident edges live entirely at-or-above the
# level (no slope bounds needed); non-incident edges get explicit margins
# as in the corner drop: a level-crossing edge crosses at abscissa X with
# |X - px v| = m > 0 (tautness via taut_vertex_endpoint), and for
# 8*delta < m + thin band the probe stays m/2 short of it
# (hprobe_avoid_level_crossing, the horizontal twin of
# drop_avoid_level_crossing); two-stage corner_fold gives uniform delta0
# then eps0(delta).  under_tip_crossing: any two band points connect,
# off-ring.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTTipCrossing.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-4: THE CORNER BOXES.  Rung 4b-3's per-edge
# dispatch corner_edge_clear quantifies over the WHOLE abscissa interval,
# so its fold yields a skeleton-free RECTANGLE beside the corner:
# [px v - 2*delta, px v - delta/2] x [py v - eps, py v + eps]
# (corner_box_clear), and the mirror kit turns it into all four boxes
# (east of bottom, west of top, east of top).  Inside a free rectangle any
# two points connect by one vertical and one horizontal segment
# (box_connected_of_clear, generic).  The boxes absorb at once all the
# glue the traversal's corner composites need: drops, rejoin jogs onto the
# next edge's corridor, transfers between passage destinations and tip
# crossings.  Hypotheses are rung 4b-3's tautness + the horizontal-
# incident direction at the corner (vacuous under the traversal's global
# no-horizontal-edges simplification).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTCornerBox.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-5: THE RING-CYCLE STRUCTURE.  Pure list
# combinatorics the traversal consumes.  ring_core_nodup (closed ring with
# pairwise-distinct core vertices); ring_edges_in_split (edge membership IS
# list splitting -- axiom-free); in_edge_unique / out_edge_unique (each
# vertex has at most one incoming and one outgoing edge, by count_occ on
# the unique core occurrence, with the seam vertex's own analysis);
# incident_two (every incident edge is THE in-edge or THE out-edge -- the
# degree-2 lemma discharging the corner conditions against the two cycle
# neighbours); cyclic_next / cyclic_prev (cycle successor and predecessor,
# closedness wrapping the seam).  Also vertex_xmax_achieved and the
# xsup-free terminal count ho_count_zero_east_ub (weakly east of every
# vertex, the crossing count is zero).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTRingCycle.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-6: THE HUG STATE and the first CORNER COMPOSITE.
# hugs_west r e q: the anchor q is off-ring and connected to e's west
# corridor at the SPAN MIDPOINT mid e (the delta-free canonical height
# killing the parameter-threading circularity), with freedom at all
# smaller offsets (what corridor_offset_jog consumes).  Steps never move
# q -- they extend its connectivity.  hug_step_pass_down_west: at a
# degree-2 downward pass-through corner, jog . corner_passage_fresh .
# corner-box transfer (abscissae pinned by drop/apex_abscissa_bound) .
# top-abutting ride to mid f.  The corner conditions are DISCHARGED, not
# assumed: corner_opens_east(_top) hold by incident_two (the only
# incidents are e -- own carrier -- and f -- far endpoint below, vacuous).
# Also: wall_corridor_clear_corner_top (y-flip of rung 5a's corner-
# abutting clearance) and apex_abscissa_bound (y-flip of the drop bound).
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTHugStep.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-7: THE MIRRORED HUG STEPS.  The hug state
# transports through the reflections: the west midpoint corridor of a
# y-mirrored edge IS the y-mirror of the west midpoint corridor
# (corridor_ymir, mid_ymir), and the x-mirror swaps west corridors into
# EAST corridors (corridor_xmir), turning hugs_west of the mirror into
# hugs_east of the original.  With the ring-side hypotheses transported
# (tautness, proper-ring via injective-map NoDup, no-horizontal), the
# three remaining pass-through composites follow from rung 5c-6's
# hug_step_pass_down_west by transport: hug_step_pass_up_west (ymir),
# hug_step_pass_down_east (xmir), hug_step_pass_up_east (both).
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTHugMirror.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-8: THE OPEN-SIDE LOCAL-MINIMUM COMPOSITE.  At a
# local minimum c the boundary turns around; the walker on the OPEN side
# (west of arriving e, departing f weakly east of e's carrier) rounds the
# tip: jog . corner_passage_fresh (down e's west side) .
# under_tip_crossing (beneath the tip) . east corner box . east
# corner-abutting rise to mid f -- the hug side flips (hugs_west e ->
# hugs_east f), as right-of-travel demands.  Open-side conditions are two
# carrier-line comparisons the traversal decides by Rle_dec.  Degree-2
# housekeeping incident_pair_min (two in- or out-edges at c would
# coincide, excluded by e <> f); east-side gap-fillers by x-flip pullback:
# wall_corridor_clear_east (4b-2), wall_corridor_clear_corner_east (5a),
# corridor_connected_east (rung 2), foot_abscissa_bound (two-sided pin).
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTMinOpenStep.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-9: THE MIRRORED OPEN-SIDE TURNAROUNDS.  Rung
# 5c-8's open-side local-minimum composite transported through the
# reflections: hug_step_min_open_ew (xmir: east in, west out, departing
# edge weakly WEST), hug_step_max_open_we (ymir: local MAX, west in, east
# out), hug_step_max_open_ew (both flips).  The x-flip swaps hug sides AND
# carrier conditions; the y-flip turns minima into maxima keeping both.
# Completes the OPEN-side corner inventory: four pass-throughs + four
# open extremum turnarounds.  Only the pinched-side turnaround remains
# before the cycle recursion.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTMinOpenMirror.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-10: THE CORNER DISK.  Every edge NOT incident at
# a vertex v misses a fixed square neighbourhood of v -- the pinched
# turnaround's last missing clearance (away from the corner the wedge
# interior may contain nested spiral arms, so the cross-wedge jog must
# happen inside the taut margins around v, where the incident edges clear
# POINTWISE and everything else clears by this disk).  Per edge: height
# margins when the span misses v's level; the taut abscissa margin
# |X - px v| = m > 0 via taut_vertex_endpoint plus
# hprobe_avoid_level_crossing (rung 5c-3's rectangle probe, reused with
# delta = eps = radius) when it crosses.  No horizontal cases under the
# global simplification; clear_fold gives the uniform radius
# (corner_disk_clear).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTCornerDisk.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-11: THE PINCHED TURNAROUND
# (hug_step_min_pinched_we).  At a local minimum whose departing edge
# climbs strictly WEST of the arriving edge, the west-side walker is
# inside the closing wedge: jog . descend west-of-e to the fixed band
# height py c + eps0 (rung 4b-2 on a FIXED window -- f's clip margins
# strictly positive since the carriers only meet at c) . jog ACROSS the
# wedge interior (incident edges pointwise via on_carrier_x; all others
# via the corner disk) . ascend east-of-f to mid f.  The wedge width is
# affine with root at c (width = (KE - KF)(y - py c), KE > KF from the
# strict pinch), so eps0 is fixed BEFORE delta and the jog has room for
# delta < (KE - KF) eps0 / 3: no quantifier circularity.  The hug side
# flips (hugs_west e -> hugs_east f).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTPinchedStep.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-12: THE MIRRORED PINCHED TURNAROUNDS and the
# CARRIER-SIDE BRIDGE.  hug_step_min_pinched_ew (xmir),
# hug_step_max_pinched_we (ymir), hug_step_max_pinched_ew (both flips);
# hugs_east_ymir factored out.  carrier_side_equiv: at an extremum corner
# the two carrier-side conditions are EQUIVALENT (one slope comparison
# (KE - KF) through the shared corner, stated for minima and maxima at
# once via the same-side product), so the per-corner total step decides
# open vs pinched with a single Rle_dec and derives the partner condition
# from the bridge.  The full corner-move inventory (4 pass-throughs +
# 4 open + 4 pinched) is now Qed.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTPinchedMirror.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-13: THE PER-CORNER TOTAL STEP.  The combined
# state hugs := hugs_west \/ hugs_east advances through ANY degree-2
# corner (hug_step_corner): corner type by the height signs (pass-through
# down/up, local min/max); pass-throughs keep the hug side; extrema flip
# it, deciding open vs pinched by ONE Rle_dec on the carrier comparison
# with the bridge supplying the partner condition.
# corner_slopes_distinct strictifies the pinched branch: under tautness
# two distinct edges through one corner are never collinear (they would
# meet at a parameter-interior point, interior_param).  The traversal's
# engine -- the cycle recursion just iterates it along cyclic_next.
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTCornerDispatch.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-14: THE CYCLE WALK and THE ENTRY.
# hugs_everywhere: once the walker hugs ANY edge it hugs EVERY edge --
# hugs_chain iterates the per-corner total step along the ring's chain
# (plain list induction; degenerate cases killed by no-horizontality) and
# the seam wraps by one more corner step from the closing edge (last, p)
# to the opening edge (p, head).  No orbit combinatorics: the ring IS the
# iteration order.  hug_entry: the east approach (rung 1) carries the
# guarded walker to just west of its first wall = the wall's west
# corridor point at the walker's own height (corridor_top_is_wall_point),
# and the span-interior corridor (4b-2) rides to the midpoint: hugs_west
# of the first wall, anchored at the walker itself.  Three-axiom.
# No Admitted.
theories/JCTHugCycle.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-15: EDGE-ENTRY COUNTING.  ho_count folds over
# the edge LIST, so the payoff's "exactly one crossing" needs the crossing
# pair to occur exactly once as an entry.  ring_edges_split_pos (an
# edge-list occurrence locates a vertex split with the tail tracked);
# in_edge_prefix_unique (positional strengthening of 5c-5: any two splits
# at an in-edge share the prefix-with-source); in_edge_count_le1 (a double
# entry would equate a prefix with a strictly longer one -- killed by
# lengths); ho_count_single + ho_count_one_in (crossings = entries equal
# to the in-edge => count exactly 1).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTEdgeCount.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-16a: THE PAYOFF KIT.  Count kernels at the
# eastmost corner's band points: the OUT-edge counting symmetry
# (out_edge_prefix_unique / out_edge_count_le1 / ho_count_one_out);
# ho_count_zero_of_no_cross; noncross_far (a non-incident edge never
# crosses a band point's ray near the EASTMOST vertex: the crossing
# abscissa is a convex combination of endpoint abscissae, at most the
# eastmost abscissa, and the corner disk excludes the near range);
# incident kernels (spans missing the height never cross; carriers at or
# west never cross; strictly straddling carriers strictly east always
# do); wall_corridor_clear_corner_east_top (the last clearance mirror).
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTPayoffKit.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-16b: THE PAYOFF RIDES.  At the eastmost vertex
# each hug configuration yields a connected, off-ring, ray-guarded point
# with crossing count 0 or 1 (the uniform `payoff` conclusion):
# payoff_east_ride (east hug of an ascending incident: corner-abutting
# east ride to the band, strictly east of every vertex: count 0);
# payoff_west_ride_pt (west hug at a pass-through: exactly the ridden
# edge crosses: count 1, via ho_count_one_in/_out); payoff_passage_min
# (west hug at an open minimum: corner_passage_fresh lands BELOW, where
# no incident spans and non-incidents are disk-excluded: count 0);
# payoff_wedge_min (west hug inside a pinched minimum: fixed-window
# descent to the wedge band, the east-wall edge alone crosses: count 1).
# Counts via rung 5c-16a's kernels; guards via level freshness.
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/JCTPayoffRides.v
# ESCAPE DESCENT, rung 5c-17: THE CLOSING RUNG.  escape_descent_holds:
# ring_taut + ring_core_nodup + no_horizontal_edges => escape_descent r.
# The walker enters the hug at its first wall (hug_entry), propagates
# around the ring (hugs_everywhere), and the eastmost dispatch
# (eastmost_payoff: pass-throughs ride, minima passage/probe by the
# pinch Rle_dec, maxima via the y-flip payoff_ymir) harvests a connected
# guarded point with count 0 or 1.  Count 0 is the descent's q; count 1
# is odd and parity transport (parity_constant_on_components) makes the
# even walker in-ring -- absurd.  parity_seam_offring_taut then closes
# H1 outright through parity_seam_offring_of_descent: the corrected
# polygonal Jordan seam holds for taut, proper, horizontal-free rings --
# every premise a theorem, no stub, exactly the three allowed axioms.
theories/JCTEscapeDescentHolds.v
# Ring-class bridge, concrete instance: the generic-height CCW triangle satisfies
# ring_taut + ring_core_nodup + no_horizontal_edges, giving the FIRST end-to-end
# instantiation of parity_seam_offring_taut.  Banks the per-predicate lemmas;
# documents the general-overlay obstruction (stronger noding needed -- ring_simple
# allows T-junctions, ring_taut does not).  Depends on JCTEscapeDescentHolds +
# GeneralTriangleSeparation + JCT_OnEdgeCounterexample.  Three-axiom.
theories/TriangleTautBridge.v
# Showcase: the "hat" aperiodic monotile (Smith-Myers-Kaplan-Goodman-Strauss
# 2023) as a concrete non-convex 13-gon Ring (hexPt shear, exact sqrt 3 coords).
# ring_closed / 13-edge count / >=4 vertices / genuine NON-CONVEXITY (boundary
# turns both ways via Orientation.cross).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/HatMonotile.v
# Using the hat einstein: the ray-parity point-in-polygon test on the actual
# (NON-CONVEX) monotile.  hat_point_in_ring -- a witness in the top bump has
# crossing-number 1 (only the right bump edge (4,2)->(3,3) is crossed; the other
# 12 edges sit at/below height sqrt 3 or to the left) -- and hat_hole_inside_outer.
# The combinatorial (crossing-number) interior, valid for non-convex rings; NOT
# the JCT topological-interior equivalence.  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/HatMonotileInterior.v
# The dual, concave-pocket EXTERIOR witness: the ray-parity test excludes a point
# in one of the hat's reflex notches (inside the hull, outside the tile) -- the
# corpus's first genuinely concave point-in-polygon classification.  Three-axiom.
theories/HatMonotileExterior.v
# Showcase: the "Spectre" strictly-chiral aperiodic monotile's defining
# ingredient -- a CURVED edge -- formalized.  curved_edge_central_symmetry: any
# midpoint-odd profile makes the edge invariant under 180-degree rotation about
# the chord midpoint (the reflection-free mating property).  Concrete sine_edge.
# Three-axiom (cos/sin clean).  No Admitted.
theories/SpectreCurvedEdge.v
# Besicovitch-Kakeya, Phase A (docs/besicovitch-kakeya-plan.md): finite,
# polygonal Perron-tree stages.  perron_stage n : list Ring is the apex-fan over
# a unit base subdivided into 2^n equal pieces (2^n triangles, each a closed
# Ring).  Proves: exactly 2^n triangles; every triangle ring_closed + >=4
# vertices (DCEL/ray-parity ready); non-degenerate (signed area 1/2^n);
# DIRECTION COVERAGE -- the 2^n triangles carry 2^n pairwise NON-PARALLEL
# directions (perron_stage_directions_distinct); contained in the unit square;
# directions invariant under the future sliding moves.  No measure theory
# claimed (deferred to Phase D).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/PerronStage.v
# Besicovitch-Kakeya, Phase B (docs/besicovitch-kakeya-plan.md): DCEL / overlay
# integration of the Perron-tree stages.  Each stage triangle is a DCEL
# face-walk -- its edge list is a closed_chain that ring_of_chain round-trips
# (perron_tri_closed_chain / _chain_roundtrip / _face_walk_core) -- and is
# UNCONDITIONALLY ring_simple (perron_tri_ring_simple, via sip_shared_no_cross:
# two non-collinear segments from a shared vertex never cross properly).  Hence
# every triangle is a valid_polygon and the whole stage is a valid_geometry
# (perron_geometry_valid), a legitimate Overlay.boolean_op operand.  Three-axiom.
# No Admitted.
theories/KakeyaOverlay.v
# Besicovitch-Kakeya, Phase C (docs/besicovitch-kakeya-plan.md): a FROZEN
# regression anchor over perron_stage 5 (32 triangles).  kakeya_anchor_count
# (= 32); kakeya_anchor_valid_geometry; kakeya_anchor_all_ring_simple; thin
# slivers of uniform area 1/32 that stay strictly positive (kakeya_anchor_area /
# _area_pos -- near-collinearity); perron_consecutive_share_cevian (edge-to-edge
# overlap); perron_area_decreasing (area 1/2^n shrinks with depth -- the finite
# shadow of the Phase-D area -> 0, not attempted here).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/KakeyaExample.v
# Besicovitch-Kakeya, the Perron area-REDUCTION step, finite (no measure):
# sliding the sub-triangles preserves direction coverage
# (perron_slid_directions_distinct -- translation leaves the apex-cevian
# direction fixed) and each slid piece keeps its area 1/2^n (perron_slid_area),
# so total area drops only via OVERLAP -- and sliding creates it
# (slid_pieces_overlap: (1/4,1/4) is interior to two slid depth-1 pieces).  The
# union-area arithmetic itself is Phase D (measure).  Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/KakeyaSlide.v

# Why ring_simple is NOT sufficient for JCT_two_components_cont
# (docs/jct-bowtie-counterexample.md).  The self-touching figure-8 "bowtie"
# (two triangles meeting only at the origin) is ring_simple, ring_closed and
# has >= 4 vertices -- it passes EVERY structural premise -- yet its
# complement has THREE components, so two-components fails.  Proves
# bowtie_ring_simple, bowtie_origin_degree_four, the parity misclassification
# (both lobes "inside"), and bowtie_refutes_two_components_modulo_separation:
# the conclusion is contradictory given the (thesis-scale, taken-as-hypothesis)
# pairwise component-separation facts.  Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/JCT_Counterexample.v
# A concrete valid_polygon WITH A HOLE, unconditional (no JCT): gtri_ring_simple
# (a non-degenerate triangle ring is simple -- every edge pair shares a vertex,
# the gtri_ring analogue of KakeyaOverlay.perron_tri_ring_simple) + the
# triangle-in-triangle triangle_with_hole_valid, whose hole_inside_outer clause
# is discharged by GeneralTriangleHoleNesting.hole_inside_outer_triangle.  The
# first with-holes valid_polygon whose analytic clause needs no Jordan hypothesis.
# Three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/TriangleValidPolygon.v
# Half-open migration, rung 1: the TRAPPED half of the polygonal Jordan seam
# stated over half-open parity (point_in_ring_ho) needs NO ray-genericity guard
# -- invariant_traps takes the ho invariant directly, bypassing the guarded
# closed-to-ho agreement.  ho_trapped + triangle instantiation.  Documents that
# the escape half and any closed/point_set-level result still pay the guard.
# Depends on JCTParityTransport + JCTHalfOpenParity + JCTSeamAssembly +
# GeneralTriangleSeparation + TriangleValidPolygon.  Three-axiom.
theories/HalfOpenTrapped.v
# Half-open migration, rung 2 (escape foundations): the analytic pigeonhole
# exists_real_avoiding (an open interval contains a real avoiding a finite list
# -- the vertex heights), the gating sublemma for perturbing a non-generic even
# point to a generic one. The escape assembly proper consumes this +
# RingComplementOpen + the JCT escape machinery.
theories/HalfOpenEscape.v

# Why no_horizontal_edge_at is NOT enough for ray-parity to characterise the
# interior (docs/jct-vertex-grazing-counterexample.md).  A convex diamond and
# its centre B = (0,0): the rightward ray grazes vertex (1,0), so the strict
# y-straddle counts neither incident edge and parity is EVEN -- yet B is
# interior.  no_horizontal_edge_at holds at B (the diamond has no horizontal
# edge), so it fails to exclude the graze.  diamond_refutes_parity_seam shows
# the JCT.v seam parity_characterises_interior_cont cannot hold at both B and a
# correctly-classified A in the same component (geometric_interior_cont is a
# component invariant; point_in_ring is not).  GREEN: ray_avoids_vertices is the
# missing generic-position guard (parity_characterises_interior_cont_strict).
# Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/JCT_VertexGrazingCounterexample.v

# Why the JCT parity seam NEEDS no_horizontal_edge_at
# (docs/jct-horizontal-edge-counterexample.md).  A valid simple L-shaped
# "notch" hexagon with a horizontal edge at y=1, and the exterior point
# pext=(-1,1): ray-parity counts only the far right edge (the genuine left
# crossing happens degenerately along the horizontal edge) so point_in_ring
# pext = true, yet pext escapes to infinity leftward (notch_pext_not_interior).
# RED notch_refutes_parity_without_guard: point_in_ring disagrees with
# geometric_interior_cont. GREEN: no_horizontal_edge_at pext notch is false, so
# the existing seam parity_characterises_interior_cont already excludes it --
# the guard is necessary. Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/JCT_HorizontalEdgeCounterexample.v

# Buffer/noder pipeline, end-to-end seam S1 (docs/buffer-noder-pipeline.md):
# the conditional headline buffer_correct_conditional -- Minkowski-dilation
# spec buffer_spec, concrete offset_curve (via BufferOffset), abstract noder
# + extractor, composing the overlay graph spine.  Plus buffer_contains_input
# and buffer_spec_monotone.  Pure-R, three-axiom footprint.  No Admitted.
theories/BufferCorrectness.v
# extract_rings_valid R1+R2 (docs/extract-rings-proof-structure.md): the
# combinatorial core of ring assembly, grounded in BufferAssembly's closed
# chains.  ring_of_chain (face walk -> ring); face_walk_closed /
# face_walk_min_points / ring_edges_of_closed_chain / face_walk_core
# (closure + min-points + edge fidelity).  Axiom-free (pure combinatorics).
# No Admitted.  ring_simple / hole_inside_outer (analytic shell) not here.
theories/RingExtract.v

# extract_rings_valid R5 (docs/extract-rings-proof-structure.md §7 +
# docs/extract-flatten-counterexample.md): the naive OverlayGraph.extract
# flatten is NOT a valid ring assembler (RED) and the trace that fixes it
# (GREEN).  extract_unordered_not_valid / extract_single_not_valid -- a closed
# triangle boundary given out of walk order (resp. a single edge) flattens to a
# non-closed (resp. 2-vertex) ring, so extract emits ~valid_polygon, refuting
# the deferred extract_rings_valid conclusion for the stub.  ring_of_chain_
# traces_valid_shape -- the SAME triangle, walk-ordered and traced by
# RingExtract.ring_of_chain, is ring_closed /\ ring_has_minimum_points.  The
# assembly analogue of RingSimple.not_ring_simple_bowtie.  No Admitted.
theories/ExtractFlattenCounterexample.v
# extract_rings_valid R3 (docs/extract-rings-proof-structure.md): the
# bounded-component structure underlying the hole-count heuristic.
# connected_in_complement is an equivalence relation (_refl/_sym/_trans);
# in_bounded_component is a component invariant (in_bounded_component_iff);
# not_in_bounded_component_intro refutes boundedness from unbounded
# reachability.  JCT-free.  The geometric "face-interior -> bounded" rung
# (= H1/JCT) is carried as a downstream hypothesis, not admitted here.
theories/BoundedComponent.v
# extract_rings_valid: the ring_simple condition.  ring_simple_of_subset --
# a ring drawn from a pairwise-non-crossing (noded) arrangement is simple
# (the post-noding guarantee); not_ring_simple_bowtie -- the raw self-crossing
# offset is NOT simple (verified counterexample, why noding is required).
# Pure-R.  No Admitted.
theories/RingSimple.v
# extract_rings_valid R6 (docs/extract-rings-proof-structure.md): compose
# R2 (RingExtract) + ring_simple (RingSimple) into valid_polygon and
# discharge BufferCorrectness.buffer_correct_conditional's H_valid.
# valid_polygon_of_noded_chain (hole-free, no JCT); chain_extractor_spec +
# H_valid_of_chain_extractor; buffer_correct_hole_free (H_valid discharged,
# only H_bridge remains).  valid_polygon_with_holes carries the H1/JCT hole
# clause as a hypothesis.  Pure-R.  No Admitted.
theories/ExtractBufferRings.v
# Completed analytic shell of extract_rings_valid (extract-rings-proof-structure
# R7): discharge the holes' combinatorial+simplicity conditions from their being
# noded chains too, shrinking the with-holes residual to the SINGLE named
# hole_inside_outer (JCT) clause.  valid_polygon_noded_shell /
# H_valid_of_chain_extractor_holes / buffer_correct_with_holes.  Pure-R, 3-axiom.
theories/ExtractRingsShell.v
# Buffer headline semantic bridge (docs/buffer-noder-pipeline.md): the
# buffer_spec d-dilation algebra (empty/append/monotone) and the
# decomposition of H_bridge into soundness + completeness.
# buffer_correct_hole_free_split reduces the hole-free buffer headline to
# exactly those two geometric directions (H_valid already discharged).
# Pure-R.  No Admitted.
theories/BufferBridge.v
# The SOUNDNESS half of H_bridge at the boundary-distance level: offset/bevel
# join boundary stays within d of the corner (ball_convex + bevel_point_dist),
# while the miter apex escapes the corner's d-ball (miter_apex_overshoots_vertex
# via the closed miter_length_sq) -- the precise reason soundness needs a
# non-miter join / the miter limit.  Pure-R, three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/BufferBridgeSound.v
# Completeness mirror: the chord-approximated join UNDERSHOOTS the corner d-ball
# (chord_midpoint_dist_sq_90 = d^2/2 < d^2), dual to the miter overshoot --
# the chord leaves an uncovered sliver of the d-neighbourhood.  Pure-R, 3-axiom.
theories/BufferBridgeComplete.v
# Round-join arc on the corner d-circle (round_arc_dist_sq_on_circle = d^2):
# closes both H_bridge directions at the corner, and the buffer_corner_trichotomy
# capstone (chord d^2/2 < arc d^2 < miter 2 d^2).  Pure-R, three-axiom.
theories/BufferBridgeRound.v
# Stage 4b depth labelling (EdgeLabel reused as interior-side flags; keep-
# boundary rule = SymDiff) + factorisation of the full H_bridge through the
# depth region (extract_realizes_depth /\ depth_region_is_buffer), with the
# empty base case closed.  Pure-R, three-axiom.  No Admitted.
theories/BufferDepth.v

# Why depth_region (BufferDepth.v) needs a CLOSED-BOUNDARY guard
# (docs/buffer-depth-enclosure-counterexample.md).  depth_region runs
# ray_parity_odd over the kept edges with no constraint that they form a closed
# boundary.  The open "spur" (a single kept edge) makes depth_region non-
# component-invariant: p1=(-1,1) and p2=(-1,3) are complement-connected yet get
# opposite verdicts (spur_depth_not_component_invariant, RED).  Its kept
# boundary is the degenerate open ring spur_ring = [(0,0);(0,2)], which is not
# ring_closed; a closure-guarded depth predicate excludes it
# (spur_excluded_by_closure_guard, GREEN).  Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/BufferDepthEnclosureCounterexample.v

# depth_region's closed-boundary guard (#91) is necessary but not sufficient
# (docs/buffer-depth-horizontal-edge-counterexample.md).  Reusing the #86 notch
# as the (closed) kept boundary of a graph G_notch, depth_region G_notch pext is
# true (the ray runs along the horizontal kept edge) yet pext is exterior
# (depth_region_horizontal_refutes, RED).  A no_horizontal_edge_at guard on the
# kept boundary excludes it (Gnotch_excluded_by_no_horizontal_guard, GREEN).
# Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/BufferDepthHorizontalEdgeCounterexample.v

# Completes depth_region's guard set: the vertex-graze case
# (docs/buffer-depth-vertex-graze-counterexample.md).  Reusing the #85 diamond
# as the (closed, horizontal-edge-free) kept boundary of G_diamond, A=(0,1/2)
# and B=(0,0) are complement-connected yet get opposite depth_region verdicts
# (depth_region_vertex_not_invariant, RED) because B's ray grazes vertex (1,0).
# A ray_avoids_vertices guard on the kept boundary excludes it
# (Gdiamond_excluded_by_ray_avoids_guard, GREEN).  With #91/#93 this pins the
# full guard set. Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/BufferDepthVertexGrazeCounterexample.v

# REFACTOR: the guarded depth-region predicate + depth/interior bridge
# (docs/buffer-depth-guarded.md).  Folds the #91/#93/#95 guards into
# kept_boundary_wellformed and re-points the depth seams onto it (additive; the
# existing BufferDepth theorems are untouched).  depth_region_is_geometric_
# interior_guarded is the depth analogue of point_in_ring_correct_jct_cont:
# for a well-formed kept boundary, depth_region = geometric_interior_cont under
# the named JCT seam parity_characterises_interior_cont_strict (not discharged).
# buffer_H_bridge_factor_guarded re-points the H_bridge onto the guarded seam.
# Pure-R; no Admitted/Axiom/Parameter.
theories/BufferDepthGuarded.v

# Phase 4 Session 2: SQL/MM CIRCULARSTRING / COMPOUNDCURVE foundational
# types (CircularArc, CurveSegment, CurveRing, CurvePolygon,
# CurveGeometry) + validity predicates + chord approximation bridge
# (chord_approx_arc / chord_approx_segment / chord_approx_ring /
